yers, and Prophecy -- tPsalms as Prophecy: Qumran Evidence for the Reading of Psalms as Prophetic Text and the Formation of the Canon -- tExodus and Exile as Prototypes of Justice: Prophecies in the Psalms of Solomon and Barkhi Nafshi Hymns -- tPart 5: Psalms, Prayers, History and Identity -- tThose Who Pray Together Stay Together: The Role of Late Psalms in Creating Identity -- tPraying History in the Dead Sea Scrolls: Memory, Identity, Fulfilment -- tFathers and Sons: Family Ties in the Historical Psalms -- tPart 6: The Composition and Use of Psalms and Prayers -- tSpeakers and Scenarios: Imagining the First Temple in Second Temple Psalms (Psalms 122 and 137) -- tBen Sira’s Use of Various Psalm Genres -- t“There is no one righteous”: Paul’s Use of Psalms in Romans 3 -- tPhilippians 2:6–11 as a Christological Psalm from the 20th Century -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Ancient Sources -- tIndex of Modern Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen thinking about psalms and prayers in the Second Temple period, the Masoretic Psalter and its reception is often given priority because of modern academic or theological interests. This emphasis tends to skew our understanding of the corpus we call psalms and prayers and often dampens or mutes the lived context within which these texts were composed and used. This volume is comprised of a collection of articles that explore the diverse settings in which psalms and prayers were used and circulated in the late Second Temple period. The book includes essays by experts in the Hebrew bible, the Dead Sea scrolls, Apocrypha and Pseudepigrapha, and the New Testament, in which a wide variety of topics, approaches, and methods both old and new are utilized to explore the many functions of psalms and prayers in the late Second Temple period. Included in this volume are essays examining how psalms were read as prophecy, as history, as liturgy, and as literature. A variety methodologies are employed, and include the use of cognitive sciences and poetics, linguistic theory, psychology, redaction criticism, and literary theory.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aPrayerxJudaism. 4aGebete. 4aPsalmen. 4aZeit des Zweiten Tempels. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aPsalm.  aSecond Temple period.  aprayer.1 aAadland, Ingunn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAngel, Joseph L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerlin, Adele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrettler, Marc Zvi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooke, George J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Kipp, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarkins, Angela Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolt, Else K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHøgenhaven, Jesper, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJokiranta, Jutta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJustnes, Årstein, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein, Anja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKörting, Corinna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarttila, Marko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewsom, Carol A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPajunen, Mika S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPajunen, Mika S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPenner, 